You can use

    public ValueA map(ValueB valueB, Date date) {
        return find(valueB)
            .map(valueC -&gt; {
                // call many getters on valueC and do a lot of logic with it.
                return map(/*some parameters*/);
            })
            .orElse(null);
    }
the key point is that the mapping function is only evaluated, if the optional is not empty, otherwise, the result stays an empty optional. `orElse(null)` will return `null` if the optional is empty.

Given the line `return map(/*some parameters*/);`, are you intending to create a recursive call to your `map` method?

Assuming you are NOT attempting a recursive method call...

For clarification, I would remodel your method to look more this:
```Java
public Optional&lt;ValueA&gt; process(ValueB valueB, Date date) {
    Optional&lt;ValueC&gt; valueCOpt = find(valueB);
    if (valueCOpt.isPresent()) {
        ValueC valueC = valueCOpt.get();
        // call many getters on valueC and do a lot of logic with it.
        return Optional.of(new ValueA(/*results of above logic as parameters*/));
    }
    return Optional.empty();
}
```

Then I would refactor it to eliminate the `.isPresent` and `.get` method calls on `Optional` entirely, replacing them with `.map` which would look like this:
```Java
public Optional&lt;ValueA&gt; process(ValueB valueB, Date date) {
    return find(valueB)
        .map(valueC -&gt; new ValueA(/*results of logic on valueC as parameters*/));
}
```

As you can see, the `.map` method is able to extract `valueC` from the `Optional&lt;ValueC&gt;` if `valueC` is present, and then the returned value is a wrapped `ValueA`. When the `.map` is called on the `Optional&lt;ValueC&gt;` and it is empty, then it automagically returns `Optional&lt;ValueA&gt;.empty()`.


In the event that during the processing of `valueC` it is discovered a `ValueA` cannot be instantiated, then `Optional.empty()` must be returned. This would require using `.flatMap` which would look like this:
```Java
public Optional&lt;ValueA&gt; process(ValueB valueB, Date date) {
    return find(valueB)
        .flatMap(valueC -&gt; {
            // call many getters on valueC and do a lot of logic with it.
          boolean isValueCProcessingSuccessful = false;
          return (isValueCProcessingSuccessful)
              ? Optional.of(new ValueA(/*results of above logic as parameters*/))
              : Optional.empty();
        });
}
```

