If I understood the problem correctly, judging by the sample data, you have a `List&lt;List&lt;B&gt;&gt;` as an input.

And based on the sample output you&#39;ve provided, you need to obtain a map of type `Map&lt;Integer,A&gt;` as a result (**not** a `Map&lt;Integer,List&lt;A&gt;&gt;`).

This can be done in the following steps:

* flatten the data using `flatMap()`, i.e. transform a `Stream&lt;List&lt;B&gt;&gt;` into a `Stream&lt;B&gt;`;
* group the elements by `id` by the means of collector [`groupingBy()`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/stream/Collectors.html#groupingBy(java.util.function.Function));
* collect the elements mapped to the same key into a list and transform them into an object `A`, which can be done by applying a combination of collectors [`collectingAndThen()`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/stream/Collectors.html#collectingAndThen(java.util.stream.Collector,java.util.function.Function)) and `toList()` as the downstream of `groupingBy()`.

That&#39;s how it might be implemented:

    public static void main(String[] args) {
